This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.

Summary:
1. Primary Request and Intent:
   The user asked: "Read prompt.md and complete the exercise following the workflow rules." The exercise is the MHPCO Claim Office Kata — implementing a TypeScript insurance policy system with `quote` (computes premium for a list of items) and `claim` (processes damage against a policy) operations, exposed via a CLI at `src/cli.ts`. The system must handle main items (sword/amulet/staff/potion), components (rune/moonstone), block discounts (exactly 3 alike components → 60 G), per-item modifiers (cursed +50%, high enchantment ≥5 +30%), per-policy modifiers (loyalty ≥2yr -20%, follow-up contract -15%), first insurance (+10% per item), 5 G processing fee, rounding in MHPCO's favor (premiums round up, payouts round down). Claims have 100 G deductible, cap at 2× insurance sum, ench ≥8 → 50% reimbursement, dragon material → full reimbursement. Error handling: unknown type, mismatched damages, negative amounts → throw/exit nonzero.

   The workflow MANDATES strict TDD discipline:
   - test-list, red, green skills via Skill tool (main context)
   - refactor via Task subagent (isolated context)
   - One test at a time, predictions before runs
   - When all tests pass, write `experiment-done.txt` containing only "DONE"

2. Key Technical Concepts:
   - TypeScript with ESM (`type: "module"`, `.js` import extensions)
   - Vitest test framework (pnpm test)
   - TDD red-green-refactor cycle, hybrid v6 (skills + subagent refactor)
   - APP (Absolute Priority Premise) mass calculations
   - Four Rules of Simple Design (Tests Pass, Reveals Intent, No Duplication, Fewest Elements)
   - Lookup tables (Record<string, number>) over conditionals
   - Grouping items by type for block discount rule
   - Per-item vs per-policy modifiers
